"create_before_destroy absolutely achieves zero downtime because ALB always has healthy targets throughout the update.
 But it does NOT prevent mixed versions — old and new EC2s serve traffic together briefly during the update.
 Zero downtime and zero mixed versions are two different problems.
 create_before_destroy solves downtime.
 Blue/Green and Canary solve mixed versions." ✅

How to add a new target group

1. Go to EC2 Console → Load Balancers.
2. Select your Application Load Balancer (ALB).
3. Open the Listeners tab.
4. Click View/Edit Rules.
5. Select the listener rule and click Edit.
6. In the Forward action:
   - Click Add target group (+ Add target group).
   - Select your new target group (e.g., TG-Green).
   - Assign the traffic weights.

     Example:
     Target Group      Weight
     ------------------------
     TG-Blue           95
     TG-Green          5

7. Click Save to apply the changes.
------------------------------
Host-based routing:

Listener :443

Rule:
IF Host = app.example.com
THEN Forward to:
    TG-Blue   (95)
    TG-Green  (5)
-------------------
path-based routing:

Listener :443

Rule 1:
IF Path = /api/*
THEN Forward:
    TG-API-Blue   (90)
    TG-API-Green  (10)

--------------------------

So the flow is:

Listener (80 or 443)
        │
        ▼
Listener Rules
        │
        ├── Host-based routing
        ├── Path-based routing
        ├── Header-based routing
        ├── Query string routing
        └── Source IP routing
                │
                ▼
        Forward Action
                │
                ├── TG-Blue (95%)
                └── TG-Green (5%)
---------------------------------------------
In short:

• Listener listens on a port (80 or 443).

• Listener rules define conditions such as:
  - Host-based routing
  - Path-based routing
  - HTTP header-based routing
  - Query string routing
  - Source IP routing

• The Forward action in a listener rule sends traffic to one or more target groups.
  This is where Blue/Green deployments and weighted traffic routing are configured.
------------------------------------------

Before deployment (100% Blue)

ALB
 └── Listener :80
      └── Forward
           └── TG-Blue (100%)

During deployment (Canary)

ALB
 └── Listener :80
      └── Forward
           ├── TG-Blue (95%)
           └── TG-Green (5%)

After successful deployment

ALB
 └── Listener :80
      └── Forward
           ├── TG-Blue (0%)   (or remove it)
           └── TG-Green (100%)

for blue green same listener only we need to add tg?

Yes. In a typical Blue/Green deployment using an Application Load Balancer, you use the same listener, but configure it to forward 
to multiple target groups.
----
Case 1: HTTP (80) redirects to HTTPS (443) (Most common) ✅
-----
Listener 80:

HTTP :80
   ↓
Redirect to HTTPS :443
------
Listener 443:

HTTPS :443
   ↓
Forward
   ├── TG-Blue
   └── TG-Green

In this case, you only need to configure Blue/Green on the 443 listener because the 80 listener is just redirecting traffic.


